{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c8e63c99-cb0a-4eba-8b57-628a5b580043","content":"The most likely cause: **.NET MAUI Android does _not_ use `JAVA_HOME`** for its builds. It has its own JDK discovery mechanism and ships its own **Microsoft OpenJDK 17** via the `android` workload.\n\nYour Temurin JDK works fine for `java -version` in the shell, but the MAUI build either can't find it or isn't looking at it.\n\n### Fix options (pick one):\n\n**Option A — Use the workload-provided JDK (recommended):**\n```bash\ndotnet workload install maui\n```\nThis installs Microsoft OpenJDK 17 and the build will auto-discover it. No extra config needed.\n\n**Option B — Point the build at your Temurin JDK explicitly:**\n\nAdd to your `.csproj` (or `Directory.Build.props`):\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup Condition=\"$([MSBuild]::IsOSPlatform('osx'))\">\n  <JavaSdkDirectory>/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nOr pass it on the command line:\n```bash\ndotnet build -p:JavaSdkDirectory=/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home\n```\n\n> **Tip:** Verify your macOS JDK path with:\n> ```bash\n> /usr/libexec/java_home -v 17\n> ```\n> and use whatever it returns as the `JavaSdkDirectory` value.\n\nIf you share the exact error message, I can narrow it down further.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"90bef56b-d7e6-44f3-bd90-f6db7fbf9997","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure with a Java-related error on macOS. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed with JAVA_HOME pointing to it.\n\nLet me think about common .NET MAUI Android + Java issues:\n\n1. .NET MAUI Android builds require a specific JDK version. As of .NET 8/9, MAUI Android requires JDK 17, which they have.\n\n2. However, a very common issue on macOS with Adoptium Temurin is the **JAVA_HOME path**. On macOS, the JDK is typically installed at:\n\n\n`/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`\n\nBut sometimes users set JAVA_HOME to just `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk` without the `/Contents/Home` suffix, which breaks the build.\n\n3. Another complication is that .NET Android/MAUI ships its own Microsoft OpenJDK and sets `JavaSdkDirectory` internally, so the build might be picking up a different JDK than expected.\n\n4. Starting with .NET 8, Microsoft recommends using **Microsoft OpenJDK 17**, which gets installed automatically via the workload system.\n\n5. The real issue is JDK version compatibility—.NET 8 and 9 MAUI both require JDK 17, and Adoptium/Temurin can sometimes cause problems because the Android Gradle plugin and d8/r8 tools have specific vendor requirements.\n\n6. The actual error they're hitting is likely one of several common ones: \"Could not determine java version\" when the JDK vendor string isn't recognized, \"Unsupported class file major version\" from a version mismatch, or \"JAVA_HOME is not set\" if the environment variable is missing entirely.\n\nThe most probable culprit is that .NET MAUI bundles its own Microsoft OpenJDK 17 with the Android workload, so if they've set JAVA_HOME to Adoptium Temurin, there's a conflict—or the build is just ignoring their JAVA_HOME and using the bundled version instead. On macOS specifically, Adoptium Temurin installs to `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`, and JAVA_HOME needs to point to that `Contents/Home` directory, not just the `.jdk` folder. Without seeing the actual error message though, it's hard to pinpoint exactly what's happening. to be `...temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home` on macOS. But the real issue is that .NET's Android workload installs its own Microsoft OpenJDK and uses that by default, regardless of JAVA_HOME. I need to either point the build to Temurin explicitly via the `JavaSdkDirectory` MSBuild property, or use the bundled JDK instead. Since the user hasn't provided the specific error message, I should focus on the most common culprits—likely a path issue or a version mismatch between what the build expects and what Temurin provides. load's JDK isn't installed properly, or the Temurin JDK itself has some incompatibility with the MAUI build system. Since this is a general troubleshooting question rather than something specific to this repository, I should focus on the most common culprits for Java-related Android build failures on macOS with Temurin.\n\nThe issue usually comes down to either the JAVA_HOME path not being set correctly for macOS (where Temurin installs to a specific location under `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines`), or the fact that .NET's Android SDK has its own JDK discovery mechanism that doesn't automatically use JAVA_HOME. The solution typically involves either installing Microsoft's OpenJDK through the workload installation, or explicitly configuring the JavaSdkDirectory property in the build. The specific error message will tell me a lot—whether it's a JDK discovery failure, version mismatch, or a Gradle/build tool compatibility issue. Since I don't have the exact error, I'll focus on the most common scenarios and provide practical fixes the user can try.","outputTokens":2454,"requestId":"1118:2D7D24:C4CDD3:E51171:69FE8588"},"id":"f6961336-e15b-4995-a06a-795cd4f903db","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:54:21.524Z","parentId":"9d1c1098-b111-4ec9-8293-b21066cb60a5"}
